title: Google\Cloud\SecurityCenter\V1\Finding
name: Finding
description:
Security Command Center finding.

A finding is a record of assessment data like security, risk, health, or privacy, that is ingested into Security Command Center for presentation, notification, analysis, policy testing, and enforcement. For example, a cross-site scripting (XSS) vulnerability in an App Engine application is a finding.

Generated from protobuf message google.cloud.securitycenter.v1.Finding

Extends Google\Protobuf\Internal\Message

methods.name: __construct
methods.description: Constructor.

params.name: data
params.description: Optional. Data for populating the Message object.

params.name: data.name
params.description: The relative resource name of this finding. See: https://cloud.google.com/apis/design/resource_names#relative_resource_name Example: "organizations/{organization_id}/sources/{source_id}/findings/{finding_id}"

params.name: data.parent
params.description: The relative resource name of the source the finding belongs to. See: https://cloud.google.com/apis/design/resource_names#relative_resource_name This field is immutable after creation time. For example: "organizations/{organization_id}/sources/{source_id}"

params.name: data.resource_name
params.description: For findings on Google Cloud resources, the full resource name of the Google Cloud resource this finding is for. See: https://cloud.google.com/apis/design/resource_names#full_resource_name When the finding is for a non-Google Cloud resource, the resourceName can be a customer or partner defined string. This field is immutable after creation time.

params.name: data.state
params.description: The state of the finding.

params.name: data.category
params.description: The additional taxonomy group within findings from a given source. This field is immutable after creation time. Example: "XSS_FLASH_INJECTION"

params.name: data.external_uri
params.description: The URI that, if available, points to a web page outside of Security Command Center where additional information about the finding can be found. This field is guaranteed to be either empty or a well formed URL.

params.name: data.source_properties
params.description: Source specific properties. These properties are managed by the source that writes the finding. The key names in the source_properties map must be between 1 and 255 characters, and must start with a letter and contain alphanumeric characters or underscores only.

params.name: data.security_marks
params.description: Output only. User specified security marks. These marks are entirely managed by the user and come from the SecurityMarks resource that belongs to the finding.

params.name: data.event_time
params.description: The time the finding was first detected. If an existing finding is updated, then this is the time the update occurred. For example, if the finding represents an open firewall, this property captures the time the detector believes the firewall became open. The accuracy is determined by the detector. If the finding is later resolved, then this time reflects when the finding was resolved. This must not be set to a value greater than the current timestamp.

params.name: data.create_time
params.description: The time at which the finding was created in Security Command Center.

params.name: data.severity
params.description: The severity of the finding. This field is managed by the source that writes the finding.

params.name: data.canonical_name
params.description: The canonical name of the finding. It's either "organizations/{organization_id}/sources/{source_id}/findings/{finding_id}", "folders/{folder_id}/sources/{source_id}/findings/{finding_id}" or "projects/{project_number}/sources/{source_id}/findings/{finding_id}", depending on the closest CRM ancestor of the resource associated with the finding.

params.name: data.mute
params.description: Indicates the mute state of a finding (either muted, unmuted or undefined). Unlike other attributes of a finding, a finding provider shouldn't set the value of mute.

params.name: data.finding_class
params.description: The class of the finding.

params.name: data.indicator
params.description: Represents what's commonly known as an Indicator of compromise (IoC) in computer forensics. This is an artifact observed on a network or in an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion. Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicator_of_compromise

params.name: data.vulnerability
params.description: Represents vulnerability specific fields like cve, cvss scores etc. CVE stands for Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (https://cve.mitre.org/about/)

params.name: data.mute_update_time
params.description: Output only. The most recent time this finding was muted or unmuted.

params.name: data.external_systems
params.description: Output only. Third party SIEM/SOAR fields within SCC, contains external system information and external system finding fields.

params.name: data.mitre_attack
params.description: MITRE ATT&CK tactics and techniques related to this finding. See: https://attack.mitre.org

params.name: data.access
params.description: Access details associated to the Finding, such as more information on the caller, which method was accessed, from where, etc.

params.name: data.connections
params.description: Contains information about the IP connection associated with the finding.

params.name: data.mute_initiator
params.description: First known as mute_annotation. Records additional information about the mute operation e.g. mute config that muted the finding, user who muted the finding, etc. Unlike other attributes of a finding, a finding provider shouldn't set the value of mute.

params.name: data.processes
params.description: Represents operating system processes associated with the Finding.

params.name: data.contacts
params.description: Output only. Map containing the points of contact for the given finding. The key represents the type of contact, while the value contains a list of all the contacts that pertain. params.name: data.parent_display_name
params.description: Output only. The human readable display name of the finding source such as "Event Threat Detection" or "Security Health Analytics".

params.name: data.description
params.description: Contains more detail about the finding.

params.name: data.exfiltration

params.name: data.iam_bindings
params.description: Represents IAM bindings associated with the Finding.

params.name: data.next_steps
params.description: Next steps associate to the finding.

params.name: data.containers
params.description: Containers associated with the finding. containers provides information for both Kubernetes and non-Kubernetes containers.

params.name: data.kubernetes
params.description: Kubernetes resources associated with the finding.

params.name: data.database
params.description: Database associated with the finding.
